<paragraph blockId="6.[125,777,1491,2028]" pageId="6" pageNumber="455">
<taxonomicName authority="Pinheiro &amp; Silva &amp; Calheira, 2015" authorityName="Pinheiro &amp; Silva &amp; Calheira" authorityYear="2015" box="[155,516,1586,1612]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spongillidae" genus="Corvoheteromeyenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spongillida" pageId="6" pageNumber="455" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="sanidastosclera" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[155,516,1586,1612]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="455">Corvoheteromeyenia sanidastosclera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[521,578,1587,1613]" pageId="6" pageNumber="455" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is characterized by the presence of sanidaster gemmoscleres which differentiates it from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bonetto &amp; Ezcurra de Drago" baseAuthorityYear="1966" box="[219,341,1650,1677]" class="Demospongiae" family="Metaniidae" genus="Corvomeyenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spongillida" pageId="6" pageNumber="455" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[219,341,1650,1677]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="455">C. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="UFPEPOR" baseAuthorityYear="1771" box="[400,553,1650,1677]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spongillidae" genus="Corvoheteromeyenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spongillida" pageId="6" pageNumber="455" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="heterosclera">
<emphasis box="[400,553,1650,1677]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="455">C. heterosclera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that have birotuled gemmuloscleres.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[125,777,1491,2028]" lastBlockId="6.[811,1457,1491,2028]" pageId="6" pageNumber="455">
Except for experimental conditions in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1759" box="[568,774,1714,1740]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spongillidae" genus="Ephydatia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spongillida" pageId="6" pageNumber="455" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="fluviatilis">
<emphasis box="[568,774,1714,1740]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="455">Ephydatia fluviatilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
explained above, sanidaster had been reported just once in freshwater sponges by Volkmer-Ribeiro &amp; Watanabe (1983) in the description of 
<taxonomicName authority="Volkmer-Ribeiro &amp; Watanabe, 1983" authorityName="Volkmer-Ribeiro &amp; Watanabe" authorityYear="1983" class="Demospongiae" family="Spongillidae" genus="Sanidastra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spongillida" pageId="6" pageNumber="455" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="yokotonensis">
<emphasis box="[326,561,1810,1836]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="455">Sanidastra yokotonensis</emphasis>
Volkmer-Ribeiro &amp; Watanabe, 1983
</taxonomicName>
. In the occasion, the authors interpreted this find as a possible phylogenetic relationship with the family 
<taxonomicName authority="Topsent, 1922" authorityName="Topsent" authorityYear="1922" class="Demospongiae" family="Latrunculiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="6" pageNumber="455" phylum="Porifera" rank="family">
Latrunculiidae 
<bibRefCitation author="TOPSENT E." box="[220,373,1905,1932]" pageId="6" pageNumber="455" pagination="1 - 8" refId="ref6170" refString="TOPSENT E. 1922. - Les megascleres polytylotes des Monaxonides et la parente des Latrunculiines. Bulletin de I'Institut oceanographique, Monaco 415: 1 - 8." type="journal article" year="1922">Topsent, 1922</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(order 
<taxonomicName box="[453,607,1905,1932]" class="Demospongiae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="6" pageNumber="455" phylum="Porifera" rank="order">Poecilosclerida</taxonomicName>
) and reinforced the hypothesis of polyphyletic origin of freshwater sponges from different marine sponges stocks.In subsequent works, 
<bibRefCitation author="MANCONI R. &amp; PRONZATO R." pageId="6" pageNumber="455" pagination="219 - 225" refId="ref5708" refString="MANCONI R. &amp; PRONZATO R. 1996. - Geographical distribution and systematic position of Sanidastra yokotonensis (Porifera: Spongillidae). Bulletin del Institut Royal des Sciences Naturelles de Belgique, Biologie 66: 219 - 225." type="journal article" year="1996">Manconi &amp; Pronzato (1996</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="MANCONI R. &amp; PRONZATO R." box="[309,365,2001,2027]" pageId="6" pageNumber="455" pagination="921 - 1021" refId="ref5749" refString="MANCONI R. &amp; PRONZATO R. 2002. - Suborder Spongillina subord. nov.: Freshwater sponges, in HOOPER J. N. A. &amp; VAN SOEST R. W. M. (eds), Systema Porifera: A Guide to the Classification of Sponges. Kluwer Academic / Plenum Publishers, New York: 921 - 1021." type="book chapter" year="2002">2002</bibRefCitation>
) reported 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Volkmer-Ribeiro &amp; Watanabe" authorityYear="1983" box="[478,715,2001,2027]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spongillidae" genus="Sanidastra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spongillida" pageId="6" pageNumber="455" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="yokotonensis">
<emphasis box="[478,715,2001,2027]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="455">Sanidastra yokotonensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Mediterranean.They disagree with polyphyletic’s hypothesis of Volkmer-Ribeiro &amp; Watanabe (1983). Additionally, they didn’t use the term “sanidaster” for the gemmuloscleres, because they believe that these spicules are a freak oxea.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[811,1457,1491,2028]" pageId="6" pageNumber="455">
On the other hand, 
<bibRefCitation author="SAMAAI T. &amp; KELLY M." box="[1045,1287,1618,1644]" pageId="6" pageNumber="455" pagination="708 - 720" refId="ref5986" refString="SAMAAI T. &amp; KELLY M. 2002. - Family Latrunculiidae Topsent, 1922, in HOOPER J. N. A. &amp; VAN SOEST R. W. M. (eds), Systema Porifera: A Guide to the Classification of Sponges. Kluwer Academic / Plenum Publishers, New York: 708 - 720." type="book chapter" year="2002">Samaai &amp; Kelly (2002)</bibRefCitation>
provided an excellent illustration, which shows that the sanidaster spicules are found in different phylogenetic taxa. In this sense, we believe that the spicule sanidaster has had a homoplastic origin and do not represent a character with a phylogenetic signal. Like other spicules, as “birotule” which is used to unrelated taxa (for example, family 
<taxonomicName authority="Dendy, 1922" authorityName="Dendy" authorityYear="1922" box="[986,1275,1810,1836]" class="Demospongiae" family="Iotrochotidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="6" pageNumber="455" phylum="Porifera" rank="family">
Iotrochotidae 
<bibRefCitation author="DENDY A." box="[1136,1275,1810,1836]" pageId="6" pageNumber="455" pagination="1 - 164" refId="ref5393" refString="DENDY A. 1922. - Report on the Sigmatotetraxonida collected by H. M. S. ' Sealark' in the Indian Ocean, in STANLEY GARDINER J. M. A. (ed.), Reports of the Percy Sladen Trust Expedition to the Indian Ocean in 1905. The Transactions of the Linnean Society of London: 1 - 164." type="book chapter" year="1922">Dendy, 1922</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
marine sponges, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Freshwater" authorityName="Freshwater" box="[858,1101,1841,1867]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spongillidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spongillida" pageId="6" pageNumber="455" phylum="Porifera" rank="family">Spongillidae Freshwater</taxonomicName>
sponges). Thus, there is no sense in using sanidasters only to marine sponges. Here we prefer to use the term “sanidaster” to describe the morphology of the spicule.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[811,1457,1491,2028]" lastBlockId="7.[125,777,215,880]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="456" pageId="6" pageNumber="455">
The new species shares with other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ezcurra de Drago" authorityYear="1979" box="[1262,1456,1937,1963]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spongillidae" genus="Corvoheteromeyenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spongillida" pageId="6" pageNumber="455" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1262,1456,1937,1963]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="455">Corvoheteromeyenia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
megascleres oxeas, and two categories of pseudobirotuled microscleres, which allowed this species to be allocated in this genus. 
<bibRefCitation author="EZCURRA DE DRAGO I." box="[260,541,215,242]" pageId="7" pageNumber="456" pagination="109 - 118" refId="ref5489" refString="EZCURRA DE DRAGO I. 1979. - Un nuevo genero sudamericano de esponjas: Corvoheteromeyenia gen. nov. (Porifera: Spongillidae). Neotropica 25 (74): 109 - 118." type="journal article" year="1979">Ezcurra de Drago (1979)</bibRefCitation>
reinforces that gemmulosclere is the most important diagnostic character in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ezcurra de Drago" authorityYear="1979" box="[132,350,279,305]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spongillidae" genus="Corvoheteromeyenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spongillida" pageId="7" pageNumber="456" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[132,350,279,305]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="456">Corvoheteromeyenia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, when differentiated 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bonetto &amp; Ezcurra de Drago" baseAuthorityYear="1966" box="[599,723,279,305]" class="Demospongiae" family="Metaniidae" genus="Corvomeyenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spongillida" pageId="7" pageNumber="456" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[599,723,279,305]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="456">C. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="UFPEPOR" baseAuthorityYear="1771" box="[132,275,311,337]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spongillidae" genus="Corvoheteromeyenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spongillida" pageId="7" pageNumber="456" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="heterosclera">
<emphasis box="[132,275,311,337]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="456">C. heterosclera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the former present variation in the shape and size of rotules against stable shape and size of rotules in the latter. In this way, 
<taxonomicName authority="Pinheiro &amp; Silva &amp; Calheira, 2015" authorityName="Pinheiro &amp; Silva &amp; Calheira" authorityYear="2015" box="[325,504,375,401]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spongillidae" genus="Corvoheteromeyenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spongillida" pageId="7" pageNumber="456" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="sanidastosclera" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[325,504,375,401]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="456">C. sanidastosclera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[510,567,375,401]" pageId="7" pageNumber="456" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
do not have rotules in its gemmuloscleres. Beside, the gemmuloscleres of the new species have spines longer than others species (
<tableCitation box="[634,714,438,465]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="2.[133,144,219,237]" captionText="TABLE 1. — Records and comparative micrometric data of the species of Corvoheteromeyenia Ezcurra de Drago,1979;values are in micrometers (μm), expressed as follows: minimum–maximum or minimum-mean-maximum length/width of shaft // length of the rotule, when possible; length of the spines of gemmuloscleres; and diameter of gemmules; *, two categories; 1, Bonetto &amp; Ezcurra de Drago (1966); 2, Tavares et al. (2003); 3, Volkmer-Ribeiro &amp; Pauls (2000); 4, Debrot &amp; van Soest (2001); 5, Volkmer-Ribeiro &amp; Machado (2009); 6, Ezcurra de Drago (1974)." pageId="7" pageNumber="456">Table 1</tableCitation>
) and with different morphology, with tuberculate spines in the new species against conical spines in others species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[125,777,215,880]" pageId="7" pageNumber="456">
The sanidaster gemmuloscleres found in 
<taxonomicName authority="Pinheiro &amp; Silva &amp; Calheira, 2015" authorityName="Pinheiro &amp; Silva &amp; Calheira" authorityYear="2015" box="[595,775,534,561]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spongillidae" genus="Corvoheteromeyenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spongillida" pageId="7" pageNumber="456" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="sanidastosclera" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[595,775,534,561]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="456">C. sanidastosclera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[132,186,567,593]" pageId="7" pageNumber="456" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
also implies an intermediate stage between those freshwater sponges with acanthostrongyle and birotule gemmuloscleres.In the sanidasters the spines are reaching the tips of the spicules and forming a birotule-like sanidaster. This finding again reinforces the idea of 
<bibRefCitation author="PENNEY J. T. &amp; RACEK A. A." box="[314,566,693,720]" pageId="7" pageNumber="456" pagination="1 - 184" refId="ref5944" refString="PENNEY J. T. &amp; RACEK A. A. 1968. - Comprehensive revision of a worldwide collection of freshwater sponges (Porifera: Spongillidae). Bulletin of the United States National Museum 272: 1 - 184." type="journal article" year="1968">Penney &amp; Racek (1968)</bibRefCitation>
that the segregation of 
<taxonomicName box="[162,290,725,751]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spongillidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spongillida" pageId="7" pageNumber="456" phylum="Porifera" rank="family">Spongillidae</taxonomicName>
into two groups based on the morphology of gemmuloscleres as proposed by 
<bibRefCitation author="VEJDOVSKY F." box="[460,642,757,783]" pageId="7" pageNumber="456" pagination="172 - 180" refId="ref6199" refString="VEJDOVSKY F. 1887. - Diagnosis of European Spongillidae. Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia 39: 172 - 180." type="journal article" year="1887">Vejdovsky (1887)</bibRefCitation>
is not longer justified. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Penney &amp; Racek" authorityYear="1968" box="[259,403,789,815]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spongillidae" genus="Radiospongilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spongillida" pageId="7" pageNumber="456" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[259,403,789,815]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="456">Radiospongilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
acanthostrongyles and birotules are present in different species, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authority="Pinheiro &amp; Silva &amp; Calheira, 2015" authorityName="Pinheiro &amp; Silva &amp; Calheira" authorityYear="2015" class="Demospongiae" family="Spongillidae" genus="Corvoheteromeyenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spongillida" pageId="7" pageNumber="456" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="sanidastosclera" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="456">Corvoheteromeyenia sanidastosclera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[277,331,854,880]" pageId="7" pageNumber="456" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
the pattern is present within a single species.
</paragraph>
